When using `styled-components` I tend to move logic out to keep my code streamlined as opposed to using inline ternaries or short-circuit operators. The easiest way to do this is to pull out the conditional to its own function, which is easy enough, but there could be an even more readable way by way of a helper function— I've outlined how this could look below.

Although this can be done by consumers, it does remove syntax highlighting and could be beneficial to have standardized. Could this be worth introducing?

[CodeSandbox](https://codesandbox.io/s/romantic-wescoff-krdnph?file=/src/App.js) 🔗 

Related issues:
- [#974](https://github.com/styled-components/styled-components/issues/974)
- [#2465](https://github.com/styled-components/styled-components/issues/2465)

## Current
```tsx
const Button = styled.a`
  /* This renders the buttons above... Edit me! */
  display: inline-block;
  border-radius: 3px;
  padding: 0.5rem 0;
  margin: 0.5rem 1rem;
  width: 11rem;
  background: transparent;
  color: white;
  border: 2px solid white;

  /* The GitHub button is a primary button
   * edit this to target it specifically! */
  ${props => props.primary && css`
    background: white;
    color: black;
  `}
`
```

## Proposal
```tsx
const primary = props => props.primary;

const Button = styled.a`
  /* This renders the buttons above... Edit me! */
  display: inline-block;
  border-radius: 3px;
  padding: 0.5rem 0;
  margin: 0.5rem 1rem;
  width: 11rem;
  background: transparent;
  color: white;
  border: 2px solid white;

  /* The GitHub button is a primary button
   * edit this to target it specifically! */
  ${variant(primary)`
    background: white;
    color: black;
  `}
`
```
## Implementation
```tsx
export function variant(conditions) {
  return (...content) => {
    return (props) => (conditions(props) ? css(...content) : undefined);
  };
}
```

## Alternatives
This could also be consumed another way which would not require a change to syntax highlighting, but this requires a little bit more code with the addition of a callback in order to delay execution of the `css` function.
```tsx
const primary = variant(props => props.primary);

const Button = styled.a`
  /* This renders the buttons above... Edit me! */
  display: inline-block;
  border-radius: 3px;
  padding: 0.5rem 0;
  margin: 0.5rem 1rem;
  width: 11rem;
  background: transparent;
  color: white;
  border: 2px solid white;

  /**
   * This can be done entirely by consumers and provides syntax highlighting,
   * but is more terse than it could be.
   * 
   * This complexity could be slightly reduced by removing the inline function
   * and using css directly, but this would have a performance impact.
   */
  ${primary(() => css`
    background: white;
    color: black;
  `)}
`
```

